An unprecedented future
Jerusalem – With my nearly 90 years of life, I cannot remember a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
No significant development of the present was foreseen by anyone.
Experts examined the past, but due to their confinement in old paradigms, they were unable to derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of today's world, where events depend even more on each other given the scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is waning. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome because science and technology know no bounds.
Global corporations operating on a worldwide scale pursue their business interests, thereby diminishing sovereignty on one hand, but on the other hand reducing racism, prejudices, and significantly also nationalism.
Due to this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically adept than their parents and connected through social networks that transcend national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The founders of Facebook and Google exert a greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent protests in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark not a clash of cultures, but a generational battle.
The younger generation knows that the way states and economies are currently run is unsuitable for the new times.
However, there are political "freeloaders" who want to exploit this latest awakening. Yet not through the further development of an agenda of freedom, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, Islamist extremists primarily take over the protests of the young generation and steal their revolution.
Israel has positively reacted to the will of the younger generation, but it should not interfere in the events of the Arab world.
We are at the heart of the rebelling youth and their legitimate yearning for freedom and basic rights, which should enable them to make their voices heard, choose their political leadership, and earn their livelihood.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, for the existence as an island of prosperity amid a sea of poverty is unnatural.
However, there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists will try to win control over less well-organized Liberals in elections and thus prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which includes the discrimination of women and the prohibition of modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of established authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example in achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, as its success is rooted in the fact that the country had nothing at the beginning.
Upon our return home, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. That is why we today have the highest proportion per capita of scientists and patents.
Approximately 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We consume less water and still achieve higher crop yields per square meter of cultivated area than any other country in the world.
What Israel can achieve, others can create as well.
We are happy to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
We must above all do everything in our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and that is not its destiny.
We are genuinely interested in creating a Palestinian state that exists peacefully alongside Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people - side by side.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, as resolving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing the extremists who seek to manipulate citizen movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by incentivizing those countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and trailblazing political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Especially Iran is a source of moral corruption, where one fosters extremism and blocks reforms. It crushes legitimate protests of its own citizens and works against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
Additionally, Iran uses several proxies to instigate terrorism against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, Lebanon, and Iraq.
If Iran manages to acquire nuclear weapons, the leaders of the country could shock the Middle East and the Near East and fuel even more extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But not only Israel is threatened. Iran is a danger for peace and stability worldwide.
The democracies of the world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it becomes impossible.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to deal with today's world.
In a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to realize their potential.
Today's teachers should motivate our children towards creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free expression
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
Contrary to that: experience is overvalued and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back makes no sense.
